 people will try to evade it. That is to say they will fiddle their taxes, not look after their kids, fail to provide an education and so on. Not all of them of course, but enough to make it worth keeping an eye on the situation. At the moment there is no legal duty upon anybody to monitor home education. The argument is that there should be regualr cheques just to make dure that all parents are fulfilling their duty. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="715" language="en" documentId="1143" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="simonwebb" date="29 July 2010 11:05am" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://discussion.theguardian.com/comment-permalink/6877614" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="1143" notes="" title="Home education: precious, not dangerous"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="86"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="87" end="715"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43"/></xmi:XMI>